Home » Math » Basic Arithmetic » Fraction Calculator Fraction Calculator Add, subtract, multiply, or divide fractions and mixed numbers. See simplified results, mixed-number form, decimal value, and optional step-by-step working. Built with exact rational arithmetic (no floating-point errors). :contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1} Author: Ugo Candido Reviewed by: Math Editorial Team Last updated: Category: Math → Basic Arithmetic Fraction A * Supported formats: integers (-3), simple fractions (7/8), mixed numbers (1 3/4), and decimals (0.125). Use a space between whole and fractional parts. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2} What formats can I type? Fraction B * Denominators must be non-zero. For mixed numbers, type “-4 1/5” (negative sign applies to the whole number). Input tips Add Subtract Multiply Divide Auto-simplify Show steps Calculate Swap Reset Results Simplified Fraction — Mixed Number — Decimal — Unsimplified (raw) — Working Data Source & Methodology Authoritative source: OpenStax Prealgebra 2e , Section 5 “Fractions” (2015; updated 2022). All computations are exact on rational numbers using integer arithmetic (no floating-point rounding during fraction operations). Results are reduced using the greatest common divisor (GCD). :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3} The Formula Explained Add/Subtract \[
              \frac{a}{b} \pm \frac{c}{d} = \frac{ad \pm bc}{\,bd\,}
            \] Multiply \[
              \frac{a}{b} \times \frac{c}{d} = \frac{ac}{\,bd\,}
            \] Divide (with \(c \neq 0\)) \[
              \frac{a}{b} \div \frac{c}{d} = \frac{a}{b} \times \frac{d}{c} = \frac{ad}{\,bc\,}
            \] Simplify with GCD \[
              g=\gcd(n,d),\quad \frac{n}{d}=\frac{n/g}{\,d/g\,}
            \] Mixed Number from Improper \[
              n = qd + r,\ 0 \le r < d \;\Rightarrow\; \frac{n}{d} = q\ \frac{r}{d}
            \] How It Works: A Step-by-Step Example Compute \(1\ \tfrac{1}{2} + \tfrac{3}{4}\). Normalize inputs to improper fractions: \(1\ \tfrac{1}{2} = \tfrac{3}{2}\); \(\tfrac{3}{4}\) is already proper. Apply addition: \(\tfrac{3}{2} + \tfrac{3}{4} = \tfrac{3\cdot4 + 3\cdot2}{2\cdot4} = \tfrac{18}{8}\). Simplify using \(\gcd(18,8)=2\) → \(\tfrac{9}{4}\). Convert to mixed number: \(\tfrac{9}{4} = 2\ \tfrac{1}{4}\). Decimal: 2.25. In-Content Ad Unit Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ) What formats can I enter? Integers (e.g., -3), fractions (e.g., 7/8), mixed numbers (e.g., 1 3/4), or decimals (e.g., 0.125). Use a space between whole and fractional parts. :contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4} How do you avoid rounding errors? All fraction arithmetic is done using integer numerators and denominators (BigInt). Decimal inputs are converted to exact rationals before computation; simplification uses GCD. :contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5} Why is division by zero blocked? Division by zero is undefined. If the second operand equals 0 and you choose Divide, the tool shows a clear error and prevents calculation. :contentReference[oaicite:6]{index=6} Can I disable simplification? Yes. Toggle “Auto-simplify” to view the raw unsimplified fraction (useful for checking intermediate work). :contentReference[oaicite:7]{index=7} Does it support negative mixed numbers? Yes. Enter them as “-3 1/2”. The negative sign applies to the entire mixed number. :contentReference[oaicite:8]{index=8} Tool developed by Ugo Candido . Content reviewed by the CalcDomain Math Editorial Team . Sticky Ad Unit (e.g., 300×600) Related Math Tools Percentage Calculator Ratio Calculator Proportion Solver Decimal ⇄ Fraction

Home › Finance › Business › SEO ROI Calculator SEO ROI Calculator This professional SEO ROI calculator helps marketing leaders, finance partners, and growth teams quantify the financial impact of organic search. Enter your baseline traffic and commercial assumptions to estimate incremental conversions, revenue, gross profit, payback period, and ROI for your SEO investment. Calculator Currency symbol (affects formatting only) Use $, €, £, ₹, etc. Monthly Organic Sessions * ? Monthly visits from organic search (from GA4 or GSC). Use an average of recent months for stability. Projected Traffic Uplift (%) * ? % Expected % increase in organic sessions from SEO (e.g., from technical fixes, content, links). Use a conservative scenario. Conversion Rate (%) * ? % Percentage of sessions that convert (orders or qualified leads). Use organic-only CR if available. Average Revenue per Conversion * ? per conversion For eCommerce: average order value (AOV). For lead-gen: estimated revenue or LTV per qualified lead. Gross Margin (%) * ? % Contribution margin after COGS and direct fulfillment costs. Use % of revenue that becomes gross profit. SEO Monthly Cost * Time Horizon (months) * Reset Results Additional monthly sessions 0 Additional monthly conversions 0 Additional monthly revenue $0.00 Additional monthly gross profit $0.00 Total gross profit (horizon) $0.00 Total SEO cost (horizon) $0.00 Net profit (horizon) $0.00 ROI 0% Break-even uplift — Payback period — Data Source and Methodology Authoritative source: Investopedia — “Return on Investment (ROI)”, accessed September 13, 2025. Link: https://www.investopedia.com/terms/r/returnoninvestment.asp .
          All calculations are strictly based on the formulas and data provided by this source. Definitions for sessions and conversion rate align with Google Analytics documentation; traffic uplift is an input reflecting expected gains from SEO initiatives. The Formula Explained Variables: \( S \) = baseline monthly sessions; \( u \) = projected uplift (decimal); \( cr \) = conversion rate (decimal);
            \( v \) = average revenue per conversion; \( g \) = gross margin (decimal); \( c_m \) = monthly SEO cost; \( n \) = months. Additional sessions per month: \( \Delta S = S \cdot u \) Additional conversions per month: \( \Delta C = \Delta S \cdot cr \) Additional revenue per month: \( R_{m} = \Delta S \cdot cr \cdot v \) Additional gross profit per month: \( GP_{m} = \Delta S \cdot cr \cdot v \cdot g \) Totals over horizon: \( GP_{tot} = n \cdot GP_{m} \), \( C_{tot} = n \cdot c_m \) Net profit: \( NP = GP_{tot} - C_{tot} \) ROI: \( \mathrm{ROI} = \dfrac{NP}{C_{tot}} \times 100\% \) Break-even uplift: \( u^{\*} = \dfrac{c_m}{S \cdot cr \cdot v \cdot g} \) Payback months: \( \text{Payback} = \dfrac{c_m}{GP_{m}} \) Glossary of Variables Monthly Organic Sessions (S): Visits from organic search in a typical month. Projected Traffic Uplift (u): Expected percentage increase in sessions from SEO. Conversion Rate (cr): Percentage of sessions that convert (sale or qualified lead). Average Revenue per Conversion (v): AOV (eCommerce) or revenue/LTV per lead (B2B/Services). Gross Margin (g): Fraction of revenue retained after direct costs (as a decimal). SEO Monthly Cost (c_m): Total monthly spend on SEO (internal + agency + tools, if applicable). Months (n): Time horizon for analysis. Additional Monthly Revenue (Rm): Incremental revenue from the uplifted traffic per month. Additional Monthly Gross Profit (GPm): Contribution profit from incremental revenue per month. ROI: Net profit divided by total cost over the horizon, expressed as a percent. Payback Period: Months required for one month’s incremental gross profit to cover one month of SEO cost. Break-even Uplift: Minimum uplift to reach zero net profit. Worked Example How It Works: A Step-by-Step Example Suppose: \( S = 50{,}000 \), \( u = 0.20 \) (20%), \( cr = 0.018 \) (1.8%), \( v = 120 \), \( g = 0.65 \), \( c_m = 12{,}000 \), \( n = 6 \). Additional sessions: \( \Delta S = 50{,}000 \cdot 0.20 = 10{,}000 \) Additional conversions: \( \Delta C = 10{,}000 \cdot 0.018 = 180 \) Additional revenue per month: \( R_m = 10{,}000 \cdot 0.018 \cdot 120 = 21{,}600 \) Additional gross profit per month: \( GP_m = 21{,}600 \cdot 0.65 = 14{,}040 \) Totals over 6 months: \( GP_{tot} = 6 \cdot 14{,}040 = 84{,}240 \), \( C_{tot} = 6 \cdot 12{,}000 = 72{,}000 \) Net profit: \( NP = 84{,}240 - 72{,}000 = 12{,}240 \) ROI: \( \dfrac{12{,}240}{72{,}000} \times 100\% \approx 17.0\% \) Payback months: \( \dfrac{12{,}000}{14{,}040} \approx 0.85 \) months Break-even uplift: \( u^{\*} = \dfrac{12{,}000}{50{,}000 \cdot 0.018 \cdot 120 \cdot 0.65} \approx 0.1709 \) → 17.09% Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ) How conservative should my uplift be? Use a conservative scenario for planning (e.g., 10–25%) and pressure test with lower and higher cases. Aggregate roadmaps across technical, content and authority improvements to estimate uplift. Can I use this for lead generation? Yes. Enter your expected revenue per qualified lead (or LTV) as “Average Revenue per Conversion” and an organic-only lead conversion rate. What if my margin varies by product? Use a weighted average gross margin based on the product mix impacted by SEO. Sensitivity testing with a lower margin provides a risk-aware scenario. Does this include brand vs. non-brand differences? If you can split sessions and conversion rates by segment, run separate calculations and combine results for more accuracy. How do I account for ramp-up time? Adjust the time horizon and lower the uplift assumption for early months, or run separate phased scenarios (e.g., 10% first 3 months, 20% next 3 months). Is ROI the only metric that matters? No. Also consider payback period, break-even uplift, contribution to CAC reduction, and strategic benefits like defensible rankings. Why is my break-even uplift so high? Low conversion rate, low value per conversion, or low margin reduce profit per session. Improve on-site conversion, pricing, or margin to lower the break-even threshold. Tool developed by Ugo Candido . Content verified by CalcDomain Editorial Team . Last reviewed for accuracy on: September 13, 2025.

Pecking Order Theory Calculator This calculator is designed for finance professionals and students to apply the Pecking Order Theory in evaluating corporate finance strategies. It helps in analyzing the preference order for funding sources and solving capital structure dilemmas. Interactive Calculator Equity Amount ($) * Debt Amount ($) * Retained Earnings ($) * Calculate Results The calculations will appear here. Data Source and Methodology Tutti i calcoli si basano rigorosamente sulle formule e sui dati forniti da questa fonte: Corporate Finance Institute The Formula Explained \[
                    \text{Funding Preference} = \text{Retained Earnings} > \text{Debt} > \text{Equity}
                    \] Glossary of Terms Equity: The amount of capital raised by issuing shares. Debt: The amount of money borrowed to be paid back with interest. Retained Earnings: The portion of net earnings not paid out as dividends. How It Works: A Step-by-Step Example Consider a company with the following financial structure: Retained Earnings = $100,000, Debt = $50,000, Equity = $150,000. According to Pecking Order Theory, the company would prioritize using Retained Earnings for new projects, then Debt, and finally Equity. Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ) What is the Pecking Order Theory? Pecking Order Theory suggests that companies prioritize their sources of financing according to the principle of least effort, or least resistance, preferring to raise equity as a last resort. Why is Retained Earnings preferred? Retained Earnings are preferred because there are no direct costs associated, as opposed to the costs of issuing new equity or debt. How does Debt compare to Equity? Debt is usually cheaper than Equity due to tax benefits and lower issuance costs, but it increases the financial risk. Can the theory be applied to all companies? While widely applicable, not all companies strictly follow the Pecking Order due to varying financial strategies and market conditions. What are the limitations of this theory? The theory doesn't account for market timing or investor sentiment, which can influence financing decisions.

